H00KD Source Code Contract that implements NEP-171 standard and clone functionalities for storage saveing purpose. H00kd contract contains all the minted and cloned NFTs. Initialization Method# init()# Initializes the contract's state by setting an admin account id, contract metadata and a contract to interact with. #[init] pub fn init(metadata_contract: AccountId) -> Self Copy Change Methods# mint_nft()# Mint a new NFT token only if the transaction predecessor is the Admin of the contract or the contract set to interact with. #[payable] pub fn nft_mint(&mut self, token_metadata: TokenMetadata) -> Token Copy clone_nft()# Clones a given token id into a new NFT. The new NFT will have the same metadata but different token id. #[payable] pub fn nft_clone(&mut self, clone_from_id: TokenId, token_owner_id: AccountId) -> Token Copy account_created_and_clone()# Clones a given token id int a new NFT when the owner id is a new created NEAR account. #[payable] pub fn account_created_and_clone( &mut self, clone_from_id: TokenId, token_owner_id: AccountId, ) -> Token Copy View Methods# nft_metadata()# Returns H00kd Contract Metadata pub fn nft_metadata(&self) -> NFTContractMetadata Copy get_accounts()# Returns a list of account ids that have claimed a h00kd. pub fn get_accounts(&self, genesis_token: TokenId) -> Option<Vec<AccountId>> Copy get_tokens_metadata()# Returns a list of Token Metadata for each token id provided as argument. pub fn get_tokens_metadata(&self, tokens_id: Vec<TokenId>) -> Vec<TokenMetadata> Copy Parameters# Name Type Description metadata_contract AccountId Contract account id that interacts with H00kd token_metadata TokenMetadata Metadata structure for NEP-171 contracts clone_from_id TokenId Token identifier used to clone into a new token token_owner_id AccountId New NFT minted/cloned owner account genesis_token TokenId Token identifier used to clone into a new token tokens_id Vector(AccountId) List of token ids Edit this page Previous « Subgraph Next H00KD Metadata » Initialization Method init() Change Methods mint_nft() clone_nft() account_created_and_clone() View Methods nft_metadata() get_accounts() get_tokens_metadata() Parameters

H00KD Metadata Source Code H00kd Metadata enables users to create new events, claim all kind of NFTs and create new NEAR accounts. Architecture Overview# H00KD composed of three contracts, one of which is external. The external Linkdrop contract is used to create new NEAR accounts and it is being called on very specific situations. The remaining two contracts constitute the main functionalities of H00KD. H00KD Metadata contract manages all the events, from creating new events, adding new public keys and closing or canceling events. Lastly, H00KD contract is a NEP-171 contract with an additional complexity layer that optimizes storage and gas costs. Linkdrop# Source code Method H00KD make use of the Linkdrop contract to create new NEAR accounts. The Linkdrop contract allows any user or contracts to create a new NEAR account by making use of the create_account method. H00KD Metadata# The H00KD Metadata contract's role is to manage all the events created and enable users create NEAR accounts and claim new NFTs. Create new event and adding public keys# When creating a new event, the event data is being stored on IPFS (example). Once the event data's CID is obtained, it will be stored on the contract along side with the genesis token metadata and the event start/end date. Event State Transition# All events have three possible states. Each state indicates also what kind of actions can be done for a particular event. Opened# Opened event is the initial state of all events. On this state, the owner can add new public keys linked to the event and users can claim or create NEAR accounts. Closed# A closed event indicated that the event has ended. An event can move to this state only of the block time is higher than the event end date. After the transition, all remaining allocated funds are sent back to the event owner. Cancelled# A cancelled evend indicated that the event has been cancelled. An event canm move to this state only if the block time is lower thant the event start date. After the transition, all the allocated funds are sent back to the event owner. Note: after closing or cancelling an event, all interactions with that event are disabled H00KD# The H00KD contract implements the NEP-171 standard in order to manage and store NFTs. On top of all NEP-171 functionalities, we added an optimization layer that allows us to reduce the storage costs and enable event owners to create NFTs cheaper than ever. Clone# Source The contract implements a new functionality to optimize minting new NFTs using a "root" or "genesis" token. This new feature is called "Clonable NFTs" and its main goal is to save storage and improve gas costs on all claim transactions. Genesis Token# To completely optimize the storage costs of cloned NFTs and avoid duplicated data, all data related to any NFT is stored within the geneis token, which is minted on event creation. The only data a cloned NFT stores is the token id and the owner account id. Thus, when fetching any NFT from the contract, data from genesis token is used to complement the cloned NFT data. Impact of clonable NFTs on storage and gas costs# After experimenting with both mechanisms, we found that, for a reasonabe NFT data size, cloning NFTs is being more efficient in comparison to minting new NFTs, where the cost storage increases drastically. IPFS Previously to interacting with the contract, the event data needs to be stored on IPFS. The CID is needed to be stored within the contrac for traceability reasons. The CID is currently being used to querry the event data using GraphQL, so make sure you are using the CID V1 format. Here's an example of how one can store event data on IPFS using JS. import * as IPFS from 'ipfs-core' let IPFS_event_data = { title: 'Event Title', description: 'description', tags: 'tags', country: 'country', city: 'city', date_from: 1000000000, date_to: 10000000000000000, image: 'some image', links: 'links to event', } const fileAdded = await node.add({ path: `${nearNetworkId}_event_${element.event_id}.json`, content: JSON.stringify(IPFS_event_data), }) Copy More about ipfs-core here Edit this page Previous « Architecture Next Subgraph »

Subgraph Main querries# We provide a Subgraph that everyone can use for our testnet contracts. Currently it provides four different objects. Here's an example of all available querries on plural form. { createEvents(first: 5) { id event_fn account_id cid } events(first: 5) { id title description tags } eventPubKeys(first: 5) { id event_fn public_key amount uses } eventUsers(first: 5) { id event_fn event_id public_key } userActivities(first: 5) { id user event_fn } } Copy Filters# Filter can be implemented on all querries as follow: eventDatas(where: { country: "France" }) { id title } Copy This querry will return all events where country is "France". Another intersting field we can filter by in the start or end date of an event. Filter by date as follows: eventDatas(where: { date_from_gt: 10000000 }) { id title } Copy Here you can find more information about filters Pagination# When the number of events increases, fetching all the events can be overwealming. Ba using pagination we can efficiently index event data as follows: eventDatas(first: 5, skip: 50) { // Return the first n elements id title } Copy Here you can find more information about GraphQL API Edit this page Previous « IPFS Next H00KD » Main querries Filters Pagination
